      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Solicitor and conveyancer fees in Brisbane: what sellers actually pay and what is included
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Legal fees are a meaningful part of selling costs, but they are usually quoted as ranges rather than line items. Here is what the professional fee covers, what disbursements to expect, and the questions to ask before engaging.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Legal fees are one of the most predictable costs in selling a Brisbane home, and also one of the most poorly understood. Sellers regularly receive quotes that look broadly similar on the headline number, then discover at settlement that the disbursements added another $800, that GST was extra, or that what they thought was included actually attracted an additional charge. Understanding the fee structure before you engage saves money and removes settlement-day surprises.</p>

      <p>This article walks through the typical Brisbane fee range, what the professional fee covers, what disbursements you should expect, what is not usually included, and the questions to ask any conveyancer or solicitor before signing a costs agreement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The typical Brisbane fee range</h2>
      <p>For a standard residential sale in Brisbane (a clean transaction with no unusual title issues, a single mortgage to discharge, and a straightforward buyer), the professional fee from a reputable conveyancer or solicitor typically falls in the following ranges:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Standard house or apartment sale: $1,500 to $2,800 plus disbursements</li>
        <li>Unit or townhouse sale (more body corporate work): $2,200 to $3,800 plus disbursements</li>
        <li>Off-the-plan, deceased estate, or non-arm's length transactions: higher again, often quoted on application</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Most sellers should budget $2,000 to $3,500 all-inclusive for a standard sale once disbursements and GST are added. Anything materially below that range deserves a closer look at what is actually included; anything materially above it should be justified by the complexity of the matter.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the professional fee covers</h2>
      <p>The professional fee is what you pay your conveyancer or solicitor for their time and expertise. For a standard Brisbane sale, this typically includes:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Preparing the contract of sale, including the standard REIQ contract and any required special conditions</li>
        <li>Reviewing buyer offers and counter-offers, and providing advice on contract terms before you sign</li>
        <li>Managing the conditional period, including responding to buyer requisitions on title and any contract conditions (finance, building and pest, due diligence)</li>
        <li>Preparing the transfer documents and lodging them at the appropriate registry</li>
        <li>Obtaining mortgage discharge documents from your existing lender</li>
        <li>Managing settlement, whether through PEXA (electronic) or paper settlement</li>
        <li>Post-settlement closing reports, including the final settlement statement and confirmation of registration</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the disbursements cover</h2>
      <p>Disbursements are the third-party costs your conveyancer pays on your behalf and passes through at cost. They are separate from the professional fee. For a standard Brisbane sale, expect:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Title search: $30 to $50</li>
        <li>Council rates clearance: $80 to $140</li>
        <li>Water rates clearance (Urban Utilities): $80 to $130</li>
        <li>Land tax clearance: $50 to $80</li>
        <li>Body corporate certificate, if applicable: $200 to $450</li>
        <li>PEXA workspace fee: $100 to $200</li>
        <li>Incidentals (printing, postage, courier): $50 to $100</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Total disbursements for a standard house sale typically come to $400 to $700. For a unit with a body corporate, expect $700 to $1,100 once the certificate is added.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is not usually included</h2>
      <p>Several costs sit outside the standard fee structure and can catch sellers off guard:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>GST on the professional fee. Most quotes are presented exclusive of GST; the actual cost is 10% higher than the headline number. Always confirm whether the quote is GST-inclusive.</li>
        <li>Extensive negotiation if the deal becomes complex. Fixed fees usually assume a clean transaction; if the buyer requests multiple variations or the deal threatens to fall over, additional time may be charged.</li>
        <li>Litigation if a dispute arises. Conveyancers and solicitors quote for the conveyancing only, not for any subsequent dispute resolution.</li>
        <li>Extra searches if the property is subject to specific overlays such as heritage listings, contamination registers, or character protection. Some Brisbane suburbs need these searches as standard.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Fixed fee vs hourly</h2>
      <p>Most Brisbane conveyancers offer a fixed fee for standard residential sales. This gives sellers certainty on the legal cost and is the right structure for a clean transaction. Complex matters, including disputed boundaries, protracted negotiations, or estate sales with multiple beneficiaries, are usually quoted at an hourly rate. Partner-level rates at Brisbane firms typically sit between $300 and $550 per hour, with paralegal and conveyancer rates lower.</p>
      <p>Always confirm the fee structure in writing before engaging. If the quote is fixed, ask what circumstances would push it onto an hourly rate. If the quote is hourly, ask for an estimated total and the cap.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Questions to ask before engaging</h2>
      <p>A short list of questions saves a lot of friction later:</p>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Is the fee fixed or hourly?</li>
        <li>What is specifically included in the professional fee?</li>
        <li>What triggers additional charges, and how are those charges quoted?</li>
        <li>What is the disbursements estimate for my specific property?</li>
        <li>Is GST included in the quoted price?</li>
        <li>What is the typical timeframe from engagement to settlement, and what causes delays?</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Solicitor or conveyancer?</h2>
      <p>Both solicitors and licensed conveyancers can perform conveyancing in Queensland, and both are suitable for the vast majority of residential sales. Solicitors charge slightly more on average but can also handle disputes that fall outside conveyancing scope; conveyancers are typically more cost-effective for clean transactions. For a standard Brisbane sale, either is appropriate. The choice often comes down to relationship: a conveyancer or solicitor you have used before, who knows your situation and responds quickly, is worth more than the cheapest quote on the market.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The value of local experience</h2>
      <p>An experienced conveyancer who knows Brisbane City Council, Urban Utilities, and the body corporate procedures common to inner-east complexes will save time and avoid unnecessary disbursements. A conveyancer who is unfamiliar with Queensland-specific contract terms or who has not dealt with the local registry can cost time and money through avoidable back-and-forth. Experience routinely repays its modest premium.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What not to do</h2>
      <ul style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.6rem;padding-left:1.5rem;">
        <li>Do not choose on lowest fee alone. The cheapest quote is rarely the cheapest outcome once delays, additional charges, and disbursement surprises are tallied.</li>
        <li>Do not engage a conveyancer who is unfamiliar with Queensland-specific contracts. The REIQ contract and Queensland's electronic conveyancing requirements are different to the southern states.</li>
        <li>Do not delay engagement until after a buyer is found. Engaging early allows the contract to be drafted and ready for the campaign, which prevents avoidable delay during the offer stage.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The practical framework</h2>
      <p>Expect to pay $2,000 to $3,500 all-inclusive for a standard Brisbane sale. Get itemised quotes from two or three conveyancers or solicitors, confirm whether GST and disbursements are included, and engage early enough that the contract is ready when the listing goes live. A clear, written costs agreement removes almost all of the surprise from the legal side of selling.</p>

